segments.text: that they could interact with their colleagues in related disciplines, particularly in the breeding world, genetic improvement.
And I think that was a sound decision.
But the net effect of starting that competitive grants program
did two things.
One, it got us way down the road as far as the quality of science is concerned in the experiment station.
And two, it made our faculty much more competitive for external funds.
And this year, and that impact is still being felt because this year
the Experiment Station brought in sixty million dollars in external funds.
And that number has been going up since 1983 or whenever we started.
The second thing we did, I think, came along later.
This was after Charlie Hartson got here.
Charlie was
but he had some good ideas, he just had a hard time getting them implemented.
But we did start the crop biotechnology program and the facility out there on the west campus now.
And that's turned out to be a real winner for us.

first-rate, cutting-edge science, lab space, and those guys are getting money out of the National Genome Program and this sort of thing now, so they're much more competitive than they have been in the past.
As the Associate Director, your view, your responsibility reached entirely all across
And would it be correct to say you were the person most likely to be in the office day after day after day while Neville Clark as the director was more on the road?
Well, yeah, that's the way it worked out.
I traveled a good bit, but he was...
He was in pretty high demand in the state, and of course when the legislature was in session, you know, how that goes.
Was Brian Neville the spy on Hayes and she was the judge of the... Neville is probably the brightest, most organized guy I ever ran into in my life.
He has a...
a pretty short string.
He doesn't tolerate poor performance or what he views as idle time or whatever you want to call it.
He works like hell and if you try to keep up with him you'll kill yourself.
But he is tremendously productive.
I've never seen a guy more productive in my life.
He'll come out of a meeting
and going his, well, right now, he started out taking notes on his laptop, and people began to become offended by the clickety-clickety-click on that laptop.
But in those days, before we had laptops, he would get in his office and transcribe his notes and have a,
have those in the hands of all the participants within 24 hours.
He could just get things done well and get them done in a hurry.
Let's see, I just realized one of the things we overlooked.
Let's go back to the department building days.
Who were the key staff persons in the department head's office in those years that you were department head?
The departmental secretary and the bookkeeper.
Oh, gosh, I had a bunch of them.
The first one was departmental secretary was Susan Beale, who is Mike Beale's wife, who is on the city council of Bryant.
And I can't remember, oh the bookkeeper was a lady by the name of Betty Carter.
She stayed with the department a long time after I, well after I left.
But then I went to several other departmental secretaries as you tend to do.
Being a small department, the good ones tend to get picked off by the larger departments.
I remember Salt and Crop Science rated us one time for our departmental secretary.
You mentioned Horace Byers.
Do you have any impression of him as the chief academic officer?
Not really.
My contact with him was fairly limited.
Harry and I would go over there when we had some business to do with him, and he struck me as being pretty businesslike and not much small talk.
Thank you, and that was it.
What about a fellow named John Calvin?
Yeah, I've had a number of engagements with John, and I really like him.
And we've come to appreciate him more in the later years of our association than early on.
But he could be tough.
I can't remember a particular incident, but you just have feelings about people, how you want to approach them and how you want to deal with them.
I always felt that you wanted to deal with John fairly carefully.
But I gained the respect for him and appreciated him.
Chuckling because working for him for about five years, and those were the brightest, most exhilarating years of my life.
And how quickly he could work through a stack of mail and come to a pretty clear decision that almost never did I want to second guess.
Did you have any impression of Dr. Williams?
Oh, I didn't have that much association with him, although I was sitting right next to him at the board meeting when he announced his resignation.
And I'll never forget that.
Well, you know, the board sits around their table, and there was a table down at the south end of the room there, and it had two or three chairs around it.
And for some reason, he and I were sitting there.
I don't remember why.
And the hangers on at board meetings tend to gather around the edges there and be ready to look intelligent when called upon and that sort of thing.
But we were just cruising along there.
They were going through the agenda and reached a particular point.
I don't remember when, but he said,
I guess a guy from Granbury.
Howard Wilde.
Yeah, Clyde Wilde.
Asked him to let him say something, and Clyde Wilde said, yes, I will be.
Announced that he intended to resign as chancellor.
What do you call wisdom in the action?
It was very quiet.
Very quiet.
That would have been, if I'm not mistaken, about 7 or 8.
Right.
It was late 77 or early 78.
I can't remember exactly when.
All right.
Let's back up then.
Dr. Miller, Jarvis Miller moved from being Director of the Experiment Station to being President in late 76.
Calhoun resigned and Matt Prescott appointed as the new Vice President.
That's right.
How did that affect you over in the Experiment Station, those changes?
Well, significantly because
What happened then, certainly when Jack Williams resigned, Jarvis literally took over as chancellor.
I mean, as far as the agencies were concerned.
And so when we wanted to do business at that level, we did business with Jarvis.
Prior to that time, you had been reporting
the station has been reporting to Dr. Wiggins.
That's right.
Did it make any difference in the way the station actually operated at that point?
Did it make any difference where it reported?
Not really, except there was about a year there where the
Folks out in the state who had an association with Jarvis when he was Experiment Station Director all began to huddle around.
We couldn't go anywhere.
And if Jarvis went with us, I remember one time we went down to visit H.B.
Zachary.
And my goodness, you never saw such a clamor in your life.
Aggie Button was rung in his office and all that.
Aggies were told to report to the classroom or to the conference room and, you know, and it was that kind of stuff going on.
So there was somewhat of a distraction while Jarvis
you know, carry the title as president of the university, he functioned in a broader context than that.
Right.
Now, then Frank Huber becomes the chancellor.
Right.
And soon there was a tussle between him and President Miller over where...
The boundary was, yeah.
And I presume we all sometimes kind of in the...
caught in the middle of that flight?
Yeah.
Where do you think the station would have preferred to report?
Well, I think of course, let me mention one other thing.
Jarvis had not been in job long until he brought Perry and O.D.
in as
his vice president for agriculture and vice president for whatever.
And so that began to, you know, those guys tried to find their place in the Sun because those were totally new positions.
And, of course, he did, I guess, the same thing over in engineering.
Fred Benson, I guess, was vice president.
Uh-huh.
And they were certainly OD and Perry were trying to figure out what to do.
And of course, the tendency when you don't know what to do is to go start looking at the folks that are working for you and find out what they're doing.
Well, they came down and, or Perry came down and put the arm on the level and said, you know, I think I'll be running the experiment station.
But that's where it was.
But, uh...
But that lingered, that had lingering effects on the period of the Gaines-Chester.
I went to the summer of 1908.
In the spring of 1908, it's been about a year.

meeting formally and informally with Vice President Prescott and with President Miller fairly often, began to realize there was a real behind-the-scenes discussion going on about where the stations and services reported.
And Dr. Miller wanted to report to him, and then he to the Chancellor.
Would you like to get more things for y'all being caught in the middle of that
I think the problem there was sort of diffused a bit by the fact that Perry and O.D.
were sitting there.
Neville reported Perry.
Dan Funstiel, I guess, who was the Director of Extension then, and Fred Benson and so on.
And so that, I don't recall, you know, we used to, there was flack, no question about it, and we used to get caught up in some of it, but we moved along pretty good.
But I don't think it slowed us down.
I drove away to town Tuesday right after lunch, and Dr. Miller learned late the next afternoon that he was being terminated.
Were you and your key associates aware that that termination was about to occur?
Are you at liberty to say when or how y'all came away?
Well, it came from the board.
Were you aware of that in advance?
Yes.
And the word was coming out of the board that they were getting ready to terminate me.
Chuckie.
Right.
Right.
See, Perry and O.D.
were made deputy chancellors somewhere during that time, during that, after Jarvis was terminated.
Did Chancellor Huber change anything about the direction of agriculture?
No.
So that y'all were able to then operate as you thought best.
What about with any of his successors, any of the other chancellors he followed?
No, there was, you know, Haskell areas, about every four or five years, the issue of where the service was ought to report comes up.
And it's still, you know, kind of on the table now, or recently.
And so that used to pop up with Hanson.
with Chancellor and all the questions came up.
And Hanson had been president of Purdue, where he had everything.
And he's covered there.
And he didn't understand why this ought to be different.
And one day, we were briefing him on something.
I forgot what it was.
And we were up there in the conference room in Williamsville.
And all of a sudden, he slammed his hand down on the tabletop.
Now I understand.
Now I understand.
So, you know, nobody really dabbled in our business during that period of time.
And I think Frank Vandiver...
I had no interest whatsoever.
I don't, you know, Neville would go, you know, sit with him every now and then over areas of mutual concern or interest, and he was always polite and cordial and everything, but he wasn't that mean.
I was back on campus in the 80s visiting, and he heard I was here, and he invited me over to his office.
and he said he had been hassled by a local group thinking that A&M ought to give a lot more attention to creating a strong program in fine arts, art, music, drama, and so forth.
And he said, what do you think?
I tried to put on a blank face, and I said, well, let me ask you a question, too, before I respond.
You were able to do one chip, yes, sir, you said.
I said, describe your program in fine arts at Purdue.
And he said, oh, no, that would go with Indiana University.
I said, oh, oh, oh, well, describe the quality of the engineering program at Indiana.
He said, no, we had that at Purdue.
I said, oh, you mean in Indiana it was clearly delineated which programs were on which campus.
He said, oh, that's right.
I said, oh, okay.
I said, I don't believe that UT Austin has a really good program in agriculture.
And so I told him I had no further advice than that.
It was because I was concerned about how much money it would take to create a high-quality program in the town.
That's such a high spike and a step in the time that I thought it would take a while to get it.
The...
Describe any opinions you had about the various presidents after Jarvis, their relationship to the Experiment Station and their interest in it.
Presidents, that would be Frank Vandiver, Bill Mobley,
We had some interims.
Who else was in there before Ray?
I guess just interims.
Our relationships were, of course, Bill was both president and subsequently chancellor, and our relationships were okay then.
If you could have the total authority to decide the organizational structure, where would you have the stations and the services report?
To the chancellor.
What about then the dean of agriculture?
To whom would he report?
To the provost.
Okay.
What about his relation then to the station?
Well, we've attempted to solve that problem by nesting all of those titles in one person.
And that's one model you find around the countryside.
A&M is a big organization, so you've got to take that into consideration when you think about what model might work.
really are the one we have here where all of the titles are invested in one person or the agencies are split up and you have one vice whatever.
and then one for academics, one for research, one for extension, and then the other smaller agencies.
But I think Ed Heiler's shortfall is that he's about to kill himself.
He doesn't delegate enough of the responsibilities to his staff, immediate staff, to get the job done.
And so it slows things down and it's hard on him.
But that's a matter of execution, not necessarily the wrong model to have.
Were you still active when Perry Edgerson was the chancellor?
Yes.
All right.
Now, he's a superb researcher, coming certainly out of the working level.
How would you evaluate his understanding of all these matters when he was chancellor?
Oh, I'd say excellent.
He knew more about the...
the experiment station, the extension service, they had a fairly small teaching program over there in entomology.
So his experience was mostly with the agencies.
And so when he ended up over as vice president with Jarvis and then ultimately as chancellor, his
association with the agencies and services, I think an understanding of them was better than probably understanding the university by a bunch.
And about that time, you know, all of these other universities began to flow in, at least the first wave of them.
Now, did the expansion of the Texas A&M system, did that affect the role that you and your colleagues played in the experiment station?
Well, yes, but it didn't happen until Ed Heiler became Vice Chancellor.
And early on, he said,
and it's the responsibility of the agencies to embrace these other campuses because we have almost a matchup with them with our centers at Corpus Christi and West Texas State and so on.
And we can do that better than anybody else can.
And so I'm committed.
to establishing an association with the other campuses.
So he spent a lot of time and effort at that.
And based on the conference we just had and the attendance from these other universities, he's still working at it pretty hard.
As far as you know, could a faculty member with the appropriate intellectual background
at UT, I mean at A&M International at Laredo, or at A&M Commerce, could they submit a proposal to the experiment station and have a fair chance of getting a grant?
If the experiment station awarded grants anymore, yeah.
The old system that I described to you a while ago that Neville started when he scooped up a bunch of money over at the legislature, between Charlie Harnson and Ed Heiler, that money's about gone.
But there's a little bit of it left.
And the last attempt to award grant, yeah.
these folks were asked and they were asked to do it in an interdisciplinary sense with other folks at the Dallas Center and the Peace and Commerce or at Overton.
And Prairie View and Tarleton have been down through the years.
Right.
Now, as far as you know, the Extension Service theoretically would offer them the same
possibility?
I think under Hyler's directorship they would, but not before.
In general, if you could give advice to the leadership
Texas A&M today in the broad field of agriculture.
If you could advise A&M and Forestry today, what would you advise them to do in addition to what's already been done?
How does A&M move forward in Forestry from where it is today?
I think they need a stronger resource base.
And I'm thinking about a capital campaign type effort.
And one is in the making through the university.
And the department ought to really take advantage of that and work with some of the foundations in the state to develop a strong resource base.
Parts of agriculture did okay the last capital campaign, but the department, and it was a function of the department head.
It was just something he wasn't interested in doing.
All right, and should they put that in the capital projects or endowment?
Endowment, yeah.
I'm on your side on that.
Yeah, yeah.
Because I think the state ought to look to the state to do the bricks and mortar.
Oh, yeah.
Because otherwise the money is gone.
Do you think that some of the foundations and private industry might be receptive?
Oh, I think so.
I think so.
But, golly, you've got to have an organized approach and use the resources of the foundation and this sort of thing to go do that.
Would you also advise the department to make any changes in its research and teaching?
Are there some new areas of emphasis that it ought to add?
Not really.
